# 📡 Playbook 5 — Network Documentation Generator

**Claude Cowork for Network Engineers · Playbook 5 of 5**

Turn configs, notes, and spreadsheets into a complete Network Documentation Pack.

---

## 🚀 What This Playbook Does

Generate a full, usable network documentation pack from raw inputs:

- IP Address Management (IPAM) table  
- Device inventory  
- Plain-English site overview  
- Runbook entries for common tasks  
- Logical diagram description  
- Documentation gaps  

---

## 🎯 Best For

- Engineers inheriting undocumented networks  
- Freelancers closing out projects cleanly  
- SMB owners who want clarity and continuity  
- Teams tired of “don’t touch that” environments  

---

## 🧠 The Prompt

Copy and paste this into Claude Cowork.  
Do not change the structure — just add your data at the bottom.You are a network documentation specialist. I will provide raw inputs: config files, IP spreadsheets, handwritten notes, or verbal descriptions. Your job is to:

Produce a clean IP Address Management (IPAM) table with columns: Subnet, VLAN ID, Gateway, DHCP Range, Purpose, and Notes
Write a site network overview (1-2 paragraphs describing the network architecture in plain English)
Generate a device inventory table: Device Name, Type, Model, IP, Location, Role
Create a runbook entry for the top 3 most common tasks on this network (e.g., adding a VLAN, resetting a port, checking uptime)
Describe the logical network diagram in structured text (ready to build in draw.io or Visio)
Note any documentation gaps that still need to be filled

Format output as a complete Network Documentation Pack ready to save and share.


---

